\hat{A}\vec{u}=\nabla^{2}\vec{u}+\nabla(\nabla\cdot\vec{u})=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\nabla^{2}u_{x}+\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\nabla\cdot\vec{u}\\
\nabla^{2}u_{y}+\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\nabla\cdot\vec{u}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

is self-adjoint under this inner product.
 (This operator shows up, for example, as part of the LamÃ©--Navier equations
 of elastic solids.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: Maxwell
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key two Maxwell equations for the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 and the magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{E}=-\frac{\partial\vec{B}}{\partial t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{B}=\varepsilon\frac{\partial\vec{E}}{\partial t}+\vec{J}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 is the dielectric permittivity (the square of the index of refraction)
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}$
\end_inset

 is the electric current density.
 If we look for time-harmonic fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}=\vec{E}(\vec{x})e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}=\vec{B}(\vec{x})e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 for some frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 [with time-harmonic current 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}(\vec{x})e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

], then the equations simplify to equations of space (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

) alone: 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{E}=i\omega\vec{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{B}=-i\omega\varepsilon\vec{E}+\vec{J}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\neq0$
\end_inset

, the other two Maxwell equations 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\varepsilon\vec{E}=0$
\end_inset

 (Gauss' law in matter) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\vec{B}=0$
\end_inset

 are redundant with the curl equations above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}=0$
\end_inset

 (no current sources), show that we can find an eigenproblem 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\vec{E}=\lambda\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 alone.
 Give 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Give possible boundary conditions and an inner product such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\hat{A}^{*}$
\end_inset

, assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 is real and positive.
 (Dirichlet boundaries are okay, but you don't need to make 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 zero at the boundaries!)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that you also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\geq0$
\end_inset

 (positive semidefinite), i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\vec{E},\hat{A}\vec{E}\rangle\ge0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is ________.
\end_layout

